document.title: Ohio’s Learning Standards – Extended with Learning Progressions Social Studies

E4E1091E033E40478C5E41CB9B968150.description: Engage with a political map of the world.

B1B582BE15424F23BE109C1CF5D2A13A.description:
Locate the United States on a political world map or
globe. Recognize other countries as foreign in relation to
the United States.

409D6F7BA6D24103BEBFC90E79714CA2.description: Define an issue as a problem or challenge to be solved.

00DA9CBDE290416BA937DD24AC536604.description:
Define foreign policy as a nation’s strategy for dealing
with other nations.

AF39E30523F74A25B075F1B4D4212FB8.description:
Identify a
current school
or community
issue.

B39E0A53820B421C91CA63F2F441AD6D.description:
Identify a current
foreign policy issue.

440C3A57173A40528CDDBE6B7B7134B5.description:
Identify a current
foreign policy
issue, and
evaluate how that
issue affects the
United States.

92C1FAAC2A674631BD9059EBC5AAB2F1.description:
Focusing on
foreign policy, the United
States faces ongoing
economic, political,
military, and social
challenges in the
post–Cold War era and
following the attacks of
September 11, 2001.

9D017B4DC5C14B10ADD6F08F3E426486.description: Engage with images of the September 11 memorials.

A30B7BC9629944C291EA35411C3E10A6.description:
Locate New York City and Washington, D.C. on a map
of the U.S.

ABC5DCD9BE264615817770A4D5A0D2B2.description:
Define domestic policy as a nation’s strategy for
dealing with problems and challenges within the
country.

CA78A5E369E84566970512F52EACA23A.description:
Understand that after the September 11 attacks
the American government sought to balance
citizens’ freedoms with the need for additional
security.

9DFC7DEC7D32499FAAE8B7141062E794.description:
Recognize that after the September 11 attacks,
Islamophobia (fear of Islam) and fear of domestic terrorism
increased.

F6E05626B4AA4168AA474A3602FA521F.description:
Identify the places
that were targeted
in the September
2001 attacks.

82FC68A0ECEE464386D8A60A86514076.description:
Describe the
significance of the
2001 attacks on the
United States.

AB6D3CB135364AD39B49B4A7D25310B3.description:
Explain the
effects of the
2001 attacks on
the United States,
and describe
subsequent
changes in its
domestic.

D8B469DDDB4741BCB272D62AED4FD403.description:
Focusing on
domestic policy, the United
States faces ongoing social,
political, national security
and economic challenges in
the post–Cold War era and
following the attacks on
September 11, 2001.

F7E1E9C4E0EE45DB9314DC903E10FC82.description:
Engage with representations of computers and
people using computers.

0E6A86E9F3B84F0099A07137D990E985.description:
Understand that the use of computers have changed in
this time period from large businesses to
personal/home/ classroom uses.

D1CA8CA9F04A4F21839C14AFB75E6E33.description:
Discuss how computer technology has improved the
lives of people with disabilities.

045E29FB413E42C483BAB7990AB7111A.description:
Understand that the use of computers and the Internet
have increased international communication, trade,
and business.

0C92FF8501164ADE80268F2400D185E3.description:
Understand that many products sold in the United State
are manufactured in other countries. Use an example like
automobiles to discuss how parts may come from
multiple countries and be assembled in Ohio.

14FBAB4E932E49D8822673870600EA03.description:
Track interaction or use of computers through a typical
day in the life of a student.

EAF2C3B272F0409190CA06D97108538E.description:
Identify computers
and how they are
used, and describe
how they affect
daily life.

54B6855BD61449AFA81AFA2544735FA7.description:
Describe the growth
and use of computers
in one or more
facet(s) of daily life.

DD0C15C441BD47F3B5088F04A2C17059.description:
Describe a
post–Cold War
technological
development and
its impact.

FAB53EB3AAF74A1E8B51AE639551BFAA.description:
Improved global
communications, international
trade, transnational business
organizations, overseas
competition, and the shift from
manufacturing to service
industries have impacted the
American economy.

CD684183407D457CA6FFF5F7C5B0C1B9.description: United States and the Post–Cold War World (1991–Present)

4F2FE75562854F0FA61EFABCEDD7F282.description:
Engage with other students in talking about (debating)
a school issue.

3B40D1871B4348648FB59FEBE6EC7C45.description:
Identify the symbols of the Democratic and
Republican parties.

5E8BF6621C95422DA02D2773EB06ECA8.description:
Recognize that candidates for political office share
their views during debates and public events.

D598E8E26F0C4699BB826FC1A745D862.description:
Understand the general differences between the
two parties views on major topics, such as
economy.
(Democratic - active role for the government in regulating
the economy vs Republican - minimal role for the
government in regulating the economy).

F6CBD563661C41C889E3BBD7C5F5A826.description:
Understand that political beliefs of each party
have changed over time.

3ED53FE44FCB46CB9A2375F901A5AC0B.description:
Identify the two
major political
parties.

C41E2B55CC524AFB9EC3C5A404D9D11C.description:
Match
political parties with
their views on major
topics (e.g., the
economy, the
environment, social
welfare.)

EAE29F1C473346A8B805197AF1A161A1.description:
Identify differences
in political beliefs
between
Republicans and
Democrats.

C20EAA97268344AC81C4C5EA7234A694.description:
Political debates
focused on the extent of the
role of government in the
economy, environmental
protection, social welfare and
national security.

F3195D5CFC4642A98EB64E88CE964D7C.description:
Engage with individuals within school or community
who have immigrated or migrated into the local
community

583C42CBD1DC45E68692AF4782E785C1.description: Engage with maps that depict different regions of U.S.

4D801D5737A840048C7CD7AAA2E36DFE.description:
Identify if the local community is more rural, suburban,
or urban.

ECDB42B4B9C945149E4546A83B2313C0.description:
Identify internal migration as movement within a county
to a different permanent residence.

2BAC0D044AE04CEF9008BB36ACDD0D0C.description:
Sort images/representations of urban (apartment
living, buses, subways, parks) and suburban
(planned neighborhoods, driveways, cars, backyards)
life.

16B48F5E0F334D3B9B6ECAE476EDAD9E.description:
Understand that more immigrants came to the U.S. from
different regions (e.g., Asia, Africa, Latin America)
because of the changes in immigration laws (e.g., easing
of quotas, addition of work visas, refugees and asylum
seekers).

0E451908D87D426B83E9B68DDB0E9A0C.description:
Understand that different regions of the U.S. grew during
this time because workers moved from the Rust Belt
(northern cities that previously were heavily
industrialized) to new economic opportunities in the South
and Southwest.

937A93DC8CC7408EB5BAB4C5039298A7.description:
Match Rust Belt
and Sun belt with
their definitions.

A4B34565EF444626A78C9A9E1A1AB7FA.description:
Identify causes
and effects of the
migrations from
the
Rust Belt to the Sun
Belt.

D76F3241399144EAA804437EF19F32F6.description:
Identify and
research one
immigrant group;
explain where they
settled and what
they did (e.g.,
home, work).

F13C53F1DE094969B690F0A9CDF3C8AF.description:
The continuing
population flow from cities to
suburbs, the internal
migrations from the Rust Belt
to the Sun Belt, and the
increase in immigration
resulting from passage of the
1965 Immigration Act have had
social and political effects.

36F7FCE194014F3DB394D2BA0FD528DC.description:
Engage with images/representations of
advertisements of new products in the immediate
post-WWII era (circa 1945-1960).

5E5ADEC3FFBE454F88D67206A6C272FE.description:
Engage with images/representations of
automobiles across time.

8AF3A61ABE4E4847BF7445F05B17409F.description:
Discuss examples of technology improving the lives
of people with disabilities.

0CCE8775670C47769D880995FEA6DA0B.description: Identify a technology used in the classroom.

0EDE167C562444C3988841B92360A52D.description:
Organize images/representations of the advances in
automobile technology from earliest invention to modern.

C464828C2DD34F60A4C770C09476E62E.description:
Trace examples of change in medicine, power,
transportation, and/or communications in America
from 1945-1994, using timelines when possible.

3C620CAEDEE04D1D98F627FB2FE247A6.description:
Identify a
technological
advancement that
influenced society
following World
War II.

DE6C3BE335D24D73A86A3D1875B6742D.description:
Identify a post–World
War II technology
and explain how it
improved a way of
life.

71871D06F8B74906BF3384C8F6C96E6A.description:
Explain how
advancements
in technology
contributed to
changes in
society after
World War II.

3FCD8F039C8443FC8AAB558F4D2CAFCC.description:
The postwar
economic boom and
advances in science and
technology produced changes
in American life.

6B928D0FFD5F49D384020C500F64A25B.description: Social Transformation in the United States (1945–1994)

F261DBA577494C82A311BCCD2154DDDA.description: Engage in actions that respect the rights of others.

007FC0A2951B4311A0EF3B49BE59DA4A.description:
Identify rights students have within the classroom,
home, and community.

60A3B35CC851499B88D0343BCD9681F3.description:
Identify that civil rights apply to all marginalized groups,
including individuals with disabilities.

86FF05613FD34B728547E08BF2F8343F.description:
Define civil rights as rights protected by the U.S.
Constitution. Civil rights include the right to vote and
other opportunities for civic participation.

691A13B92DEC49FAA4A7CE0EDF4E23C5.description:
Understand that civil rights have been extended
to marginalized groups over time.

E793E4E1AA3746B496AF47E01A352614.description:
Understand that the U.S. Constitution protects the
rights of all citizens, but some citizens were denied their
rights in practice (e.g., poll taxes, literacy tests, limited
voting participation).

493DA771C6964C29B5792F16CB1C87C7.description:
Investigate protest methods used by marginalized
groups, including court actions, non-violent protests,
militarized organizations, and legislative processes.

2B3B4115962346EBB4DF01746F474207.description:
Identify a right of
women, African
Americans or
minorities were
fighting for during
the civil rights era.

0451F3F0CE744D59A947AFAEAE7D06F4.description:
Identify a famous
African American and/
or woman and their
contributions to post–
World War II society.

7E3E8A456F4B488F8CE93BB2E21BF2E6.description:
Explain how
African Americans
and women
continued their
efforts to gain their
civil rights
following World
War II.

690627A274AE42F9B4EB3073AEFD7B9F.description:
Following World
War II, the United States
experienced a struggle for
racial and gender equality and
the expansion of civil rights.

500651EF3D4748A29A1254B102B70961.description:
Engage with maps during discussions about the Cold
War era.

99F12DC540CB45DB890CA5A4E78C668A.description: Locate Korea and Vietnam on a map.

084772873BC8441E851007431662EDBD.description: Define conflict as a serious disagreement or argument.

EE4A763F276F4BECBDBE2776FA52D2D6.description:
Recognize that the Cold War was a state of conflict
between primarily the U.S. and the U.S.S.R. during
which no direct military action was taken.

FB296B8E65894677BA71DFC32A89A376.description:
Define the conflict between U.S. and the U.S.S.R.
as competing for global power and influence.

8F37F1E5E9C7480CA24004F1977DEB13.description:
Define containment as efforts to limit the spread
of communism to additional countries.

2D9305C84C9C4D068D579616DF917243.description:
Understand that the U.S. intervened in conflicts in
both Korea and Vietnam in an effort to stop the spread
of communism.

B03824B9E966406382F5AE2D278986A3.description:
Recognize that U.S. involvement in Vietnam
angered many Americans who protested openly.

D1B226DCB3A549D7B62804DEE0FDA3E5.description:
Identify countries
involved in the
Korean and/or
Vietnam wars.

E5733F38403E430C91BD8EE213387892.description:
Explain how Korea
and/or Vietnam
exemplified the
policy of
containment
during the Cold
War.

2AC65C28273E484B86C7793FDDAE686B.description:
The Cold War
and conflicts in Korea and
Vietnam influenced domestic
and international politics.

3D6E5408A64B4085BC948FF8E96B2FB9.description:
Engage in watching documentary footage related to
the McCarthy hearings.

5472A4A4BDE44C4C8DFEA17F40A296E2.description: Observe hostility present in the McCarthy hearings.

3A465B5B940A4E07A65705CDE1935769.description:
Understand that accusations of communist activity
destroyed some personal lives and professional
careers.

574FCBDE9277415CB52D5BBCCA90027C.description:
Recall a time when someone experienced being
wrongly accused.

FB69802B90404FA698D4CC69E6F0496E.description:
Identify U.S. Senator McCarthy as the instigator of
attempts to identify suspected communists
operating inside the U.S.

C93D2AF78B504165BFC9E6987B6B9600.description:
Understand that the Second Red Scare was a renewed
fear of communism during which Americans felt that
communists were secretly working and living in the
U.S.

253437BE585F4583A831EC0DAAAEB2C2.description:
Recognize that the Cold War was a state of conflict
between primarily the U.S. and the U.S.S.R. during
which no direct military action was taken.

D46B0EC97F0144C4BB5743E1923E6404.description:
Identify people who
were influential
during the Cold
War.

50D030D9FF994458922FB0CA1BD45642.description:
Explain what the
term cold in Cold War
means.

95F77B807C2A462DA5FE534388B8B1E1.description:
Explain reasons for
Cold War fears.

549E84AB1E48411FA48030FB21102E36.description:
The Second
Red Scare and McCarthyism
reflected Cold War fears in
American society.

F1E4592DCEC242A4AEC215CF4BBE7133.description:
Engage with maps showing countries as communist
or democratic.

25ECDFC1BD1745E8BDCC2FCD6CFF4CCD.description:
Label map of prominent countries as communist
or democratic.

3258CBC30B774C6592F833491D6F7FA4.description:
Define democracy as a political system wherein the
government is elected by citizens.

9AB897588EEE41F8B6D1E7CC361FCCA0.description:
Define communism as a political system wherein all
property is publicly owned by the people collectively
and controlled by the government.

AD470979E5B9485EB8AFC7C54EBE0AA0.description:
Define policy of containment as efforts to limit the spread
of communism to additional countries.

C04145934C7149C6BF54F6BF4FA37A1C.description:
Identify a
communist country
and a democratic
country from the
Cold War era.

F29E2E8A38084B73B769934F300D3A93.description:
Explain the difference
between communism
and democracy.

03A760E6DBFB4D2594861BE1F4CADDC9.description:
Describe how
the United
States tried to
contain
communism during
the Cold War

911A678492094C11860F391123AA7341.description:
The United
States followed a policy of
containment during the Cold
War in response to the spread
of communism.

E5F32CE6CADA40FD8573645E388735EE.description:
Engage with images showing the rings of destruction
from an atomic weapon.

41ED20473D244F57944CB69373F65C3A.description:
Engage with images showing atomic weapons
tests (mushroom cloud).

5D84AC2D475D4015959F4D0368C118F0.description: Relate nuclear to the nucleus of an atom.

6D107B52E8CA4B2CAC02F7D0CA137424.description:
Define nuclear age as beginning in 1945 with the first
use of atomic weapons and an increase in the use of
nuclear energy.

E1AB50A2D15744D691BA7DC915FF349F.description:
During the nuclear age, superpowers were defined
as countries that had atomic weapons.

2C1F3B1CFA2744F8806F8EC299AAB15C.description:
Understand that the use of atomic weapons represented
a significant increase in destructive power and military
strength.

63238D38A98041658DB59F01389BE141.description:
Recognize that the U.S. became more powerful
internationally after the use of two atomic weapons
that ended WWII.

E18E80139F054A248450523925107965.description:
Identify the highly
destructive weapon
created in the
nuclear age.

BF949EE4308A46B79BF7BADEAC5688D6.description:
Explain how
atomic weapons
and world
superpowers are
related.

2A042C7A82784F47B99EC498F543B807.description:
Use of atomic
weapons changed the nature
of war, altered the balance of
power and began the nuclear
age.

834DF40825DB4E41B6C26E104621CE79.description:
Engage with objects or images representing
resources that might have been limited during WWII.

DE092545B4D346709FCEC4E1B1EBC2FA.description:
Identify the needs required to maintain a home and
family (shelter, food, electricity, water, etc.).

D9ED706746DE423FAAD2E6D26DF9AC85.description:
Identify effects that might emerge with shortages of
food, water, housing, etc.

40F43B1F498D49EE8B1DEF124331535A.description:
Define rationing as conserving resources by allotting
fixed amounts of resources during a shortage.

EE51317B8B724DDD86FFC1BD11B47CD5.description: Identify people as resources used in the war effort.

93D71896E2704D83BDEA6E94FED3EA57.description:
Understand that the U.S. prioritized resources for use
by the military in fighting WWII, resulting in shortages
and rationing at home.

EDE063B36F2E48F3B7726F4B9B8E4AD0.description:
Recognize that African Americans participated in
military and other war efforts yet continued to be
discriminated against at home.

3BF41073DDDE41D9B6FCADFF2FC10001.description:
Opportunities in the workplace expanded for women
and minorities.

8D5DE9A6B3494042BC4A9C2C603FB078.description:
Describe what
rationing of supplies
might mean to a
family.

A0CCEF7A7C354C5094ADDB4464F71B92.description:
Explain how the
mobilization of
resources during
World War II
affected American
society.

A78ADECA5DDC4246A105AE943A68484E.description:
United States
policy and mobilization of
its economic and military
resources during World
War II affected American
society. Despite
mistreatment, marginalized
groups played important
roles in the war effort while
continuing to protest unfair
treatment.

843CA6301030441D95C9FFD4C5D57353.description: Engage by giving attention to an observed problem.

FE72C735793F4F1D8A6C32A8BB5BA4A1.description:
Describe a time when you worked alone and a time
when you worked together with others in a group.

80B794E3251E4C32A238A5F005AA60C5.description: Define the root terms isolation and intervention.

25C7A25BE3FF4EE089F3D36DB3FACB67.description:
Discuss choices to intervene or ignore around
an observed problem.

BFCB6E07B04149EDB4CC56F50A5F4E7A.description:
Define interventionist policies as involvement in the
affairs of other countries to attain a favorable outcome.

8EAEDB4BFD2347B88EC62271CD4BFC40.description:
Define isolationism as a policy of remaining apart
from other countries and avoid involvement in
international affairs.

61399892992D4DFBAAA25D7D7C04C20D.description:
Identify that interventionist and isolationist are
opposite approaches to foreign affairs.

3DE92B8693DA4EB4B438B6AC07524875.description:
Understand that the U.S. government changed foreign
affairs policies from interventionist (WWI), to
isolationist (post WWI), back to interventionist (WWII).

F7B2A6464F014CC293B40B1B897B8556.description:
Identify the results
of an agreement or
disagreement.

9A2DF85482474F7397E79A39469120AF.description:
List
one pro-isolationist
argument and one
pro-interventionist
argument.

C4EAD81C21964DA1B72B26D3B674B594.description:
Describe the
events that
brought the United
States into World
War II.

687C836B3DFF4CD4959B1F17DCE3480E.description:
During the
1930s, the U.S. government
attempted to distance
the country from earlier
interventionist policies in
the Western Hemisphere,
as well as retain an
isolationist approach to
events in Europe and Asia
until the beginning of WWII.

5A96C370A2F74B78B94CD54F985D4F5A.description: Engage with tools used in banking.

0317501AFE124C849432D2560BB0E031.description: Compare lifestyles with and without employment.

E8112DA36006407E89A2E217966D24EE.description:
Understand how causes lead to effects using
classroom examples.

780A737E60AF442DB8A724EC0F0B8999.description:
Understand that people have wants and needs
that require money.

53182CD12AE642E3ADBB3C7F61715F0C.description:
Understand that people deposit money from earnings
into banks with access to use their money at any time.

1F920A9DDD1D43288D9368B9F3E24C90.description:
Understand that consumers can request loans from banks
(credit) in which they will have to pay the money back
over time with interest.

A11148F893D6468BBE52292E45A8E6BB.description:
Understand that prior to the Great Depression banks
were independent and decided how much money to loan
and to whom.

7A7031122A2F44688745899EEC730B5C.description:
Map sequential events of the Great Depression (people
use banks for loans and savings, stock market crashes,
people lose faith in banks, people request their savings in
cash, banks call back loan monies to pay out cash from
savings, banks sell all assets to cover cash savings, no
money to cover cash payouts, banks begin to fail, people
can’t pay their bills because they can’t access their
money, people lose assets, businesses fail, workers lose
jobs).

B5FAAA1DA87649FA87F7FB6DC1809F88.description:
Understand that a banking panic arises when many
customers lose confidence in the banks at the same
time and demand their deposits in cash; Banks do not
have enough cash to meet the demand and need to take
out loans and often fail (go out of business).

76F80F351319459CB64DDC9F86EF9440.description:
Identify the Great Depression as an economic crisis
resulting from the lack of regulation of the economy by
the federal government.

0BD3917ECA17470380630B3C2F537451.description:
Understand that prior to the Great Depression the
federal government provided little regulation of the
banking system, leading to high corporate and consumer
debt.

424B2092E58F4E1C90894EDBCCEC055F.description:
Understand that during the Great Depression the role
of the federal government expanded in an effort to
create jobs (e.g., government hired workers for
construction projects) and regulate the economy (e.g.,
Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation FDIC).

5EC5660A07734589868404D9A096DC9A.description:
Identify the Great
Depression as a
time when millions
of people were
unemployed and
had little money.

254DC174850F4272BE372D98CE399CAC.description:
Describe life during
the Great Depression.

B0B22138694E40F182E57F17B178F501.description:
Explain one reason
for the Great
Depression.

F5A6A4C9EDFB4585BCA24DCDEFB54AD0.description:
The Great
Depression was caused,
in part, by the federal
government’s monetary
policies, stock-market
speculation, and
increasing consumer debt.
The role of the federal
government expanded as
a result of the Great
Depression.

E37BB06FC7214C15AA37DC53D8609463.description:
Engage with images or objects representing
movements for social change.

65AA75F49D6D4E3A8843B7A81C050216.description:
Identify with groups of people involved in social
change movements.

64AD84837B0245C6A35761678A85B3A0.description:
Identify that emerging tensions and intolerance
from earlier eras led to the need for social change.

E8E0BFC392EE43F5B12AA180348B48C9.description:
Identify Prohibition as a movement to ban production
and sale of alcohol, resulting in the 18th Amendment.

83279A7E34074CACB7D7918A16CF438E.description:
Identify women’s suffrage as the effort to expand
voting rights to women, resulting in the 19th
Amendment.

5293C153F2794EECA4DCC5EBFA15C161.description:
Identify African American migration as the movement of
African Americans from rural south to northern cities for
job opportunities and social freedoms.

90A435C377934EA28044DC3DAFC49880.description:
Identify the Harlem Renaissance as an intellectual,
social, and artistic movement centered in the African
American community of Harlem, NY (e.g., music,
literature, painting, public social events).
